 lens of disability, using an interdisciplinary approach to examine the lives of disabled miners and their families. A diverse range of sources are used to examine the economic, social, political and cultural impact of disability in the coal industry, looking beyond formal coal company and union records to include autobiographies, novels and existing oral testimony. It argues that, far from being excluded entirely from British industry, disability and disabled people were central to its development. The book will appeal to students and academics interested in disability history, disability studies, social and cultural history and representations of disability in literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCoal mines and miningzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aDisability.  acoal.  aillness.  aimpairment.  aindustrialization.  ainjury.  aliterature.  amedicalization.  apoliticisation.  awelfare.1 aBohata, Kirsti, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Alexandra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJones, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMantin, Mike, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMantin, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThompson, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526124326zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526124326zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.deg